ata":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/6439f89127781262d742b5a4f9ea9c4798fa2fca","altText":"Barry Hines, Hoyland Common, 1970.","photographer":"John Hall","source":"The Guardian","credit":"Photograph: John Hall for the Guardian","mediaId":"6439f89127781262d742b5a4f9ea9c4798fa2fca","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/6439f89127781262d742b5a4f9ea9c4798fa2fca/0_143_3546_2128/3546.jpg","width":"3546","height":"2128"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/6439f89127781262d742b5a4f9ea9c4798fa2fca/0_143_3546_2128/master/3546.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/6439f89127781262d742b5a4f9ea9c4798fa2fca","altText":"Barry Hines, Hoyland Common, 1970.","photographer":"John Hall","source":"The Guardian","credit":"Photograph: John Hall for the Guardian","mediaId":"6439f89127781262d742b5a4f9ea9c4798fa2fca","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/6439f89127781262d742b5a4f9ea9c4798fa2fca/0_143_3546_2128/master/3546.jpg","width":"3546","height":"2128","isMaster":"true"}}]}],"tags":[{"id":"books/books","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"film/kes","sectionId":"film","webTitle":"Kes","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/kes","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/kes","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/series/from-the-archive","sectionId":"theguardian","webTitle":"From the Guardian archive","type":"series","description":"Historical articles from the Guardian archive, compiled by <a href=\"https://twitter.com/guardianlibrary\">@guardianlibrary</a>. See also <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/from-the-archive-blog\">From the archive blog</a>. For content from 1791 onwards visit the <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/info/2012/jul/25/digital-archive-notice\">Guardian & Observer digital archive</a>.","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/series/from-the-archive","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/series/from-the-archive","sectionName":"From the Guardian","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/features","webTitle":"Features","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/features","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/features","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"id":"childrens-books-site/2016/mar/21/room-on-the-roof-ruskin-bond-review","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"type":"article","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webTitle":"Room on the Roof by Ruskin Bond - review","webPublicationDate":"2016-03-21T12:00:07Z","fields":{"wordcount":"938","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4h6nb","standfirst":"<p>‘a simple story made into such a touching and sad book’</p>","body":"<p>Room on the Roof is about an orphaned boy named Rusty who has no real family after his parents’ death. He is very lonely and sad and even though he lives with his guardian (Mr. John Harrison), he doesn’t feel at home. Rusty is going through several emotions: he is confused, obliged, helpless, lonely and sad. He is confused because he is a young boy between the age of an adult and child and doesn’t know who to follow or what his future holds. He is obliged to follow the orders and rules of his guardian and dares not disobey him. He feels helpless because he knows that if he disobeys Mr. John, he will get caned. Rusty doesn’t have any real friends and he is so very lonely in his guardian’s house. </p> <p>Even though Rusty is half-Indian, John doesn’t let Rusty near the bazaar for a reason: John thinks that Indians are very dirty and this story is written just after the British had ruled over India, so he must have felt more superior! </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"d98d062df1028815327860380319b0d7ff03eb6f\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/d98d062df1028815327860380319b0d7ff03eb6f/0_0_229_350/229.jpg\" alt=\"The Room on the Roof\" width=\"229\" height=\"350\" class=\"gu-image\" /> </figure>  <p>One day, Rusty decides to get some fresh air and takes a walk while his guardian was away in Delhi. After walking through the forest, he stops in front of the bazaar and his mind is arguing with his instinct. His mind is saying, <em>Don’t go! You will get into trouble</em>. But his instinct is saying, <em>Go! You have your own heart and mind. You don’t have to live under rules all the time</em>. Rusty chooses to follow his instinct and steps into the bazaar. </p> <p>He has made a good choice. Up until now, Rusty doesn’t have any hope or confidence but then he meets a kind boy named Somi and makes friends with him. Somi and his friends become Rusty’s hope and confidence, and Somi and Ranbir are really kind to Rusty. When Rusty returns home, he finds that his guardian has returned early and gets caned for going to the bazaar. The next day, he goes to play Holi with Ranbir and once again gets caned. Rusty now knows what he has to do. He starts to live his own life and runs away from his guardian’s house. Rusty finds Somi who supports him a lot. </p> <p>Slowly, from a confused boy, Rusty turns into a confident and independent young man! He gets a job teaching English to a boy named Kishen, in return for a tiny room on the roof and food. He finds a loving and fun family, his independence, and even finds his ‘first love’ in Kishen’s mother Meena. The story takes a turn, when he loses all his friends and his first love too. Now Rusty’s last source of confidence and hope has gone away and his lonely days return. Rusty spends his sad days looking out at the window and once again, plans to run away. He decides to go back to England but before doing so, he wants to say a last goodbye to his friends and finds Kishen who convinces him to change his mind about returning to the UK. Instead, the two walk away together to form their own new world and life without worrying about anything else.</p> <p> <strong>What I like about the book:</strong></p> <p>I like this book because it was written from a teenager’s perspective. The author was seventeen when he wrote this and the story was inspired by his own experiences when he lived in Dehra. He wrote this story because he too was feeling some of the emotions that Rusty was feeling in the story. And for that reason, he decided that he would never make any revisions so readers could understand how it feels to be seventeen. </p> <p>It was a great read because it has a lot of different emotions and I like the way Ruskin Bond has written it: a simple story made into such a touching and sad book. </p> <p>There were a few funny descriptions, such as when Ruskin Bond described a situation as: ‘When a butterfly landed on the missionary’s wife’s palatial bosom….’ I laughed a lot and when my mum read it, she also laughed. </p> <p>After reading Room on The Roof, I am looking forward to reading a few of Ruskin Bond’s other stories. I wonder why children of my generation don’t read more of his books. Here are some books I am interested in reading from his collection: Panther’s Moon and Other Stories, The Hidden Pool, and Rusty goes to London. </p> <p>I think the author has explained an important message in this book. Rusty’s guardian seems to be a little racist, who chooses to live in India but not mix with the people there. I think if people live in a country, they should mix with the people and appreciate their culture. </p> <p>The lesson in this story for me is to remain open as Rusty was and to follow my instincts. If Rusty had not becomes friends with the people of the bazaar he would never have had all the wonderful experiences in the story. </p> <p>Ruskin Bond reminds me of Roald Dahl because they both use interesting language and really funny phrases to describe their characters and their stories. They both write simple but wonderful stories. Even though, Roald Dahl is more fantastical and Ruskin Bond’s stories feel like memoirs but presented as a story. </p> <p> I WOULD GIVE THIS BOOK A 9 OUT OF 10 RATING!</p> <h2><strong>Want to tell the world about a book you’ve read? <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">Join the site</a> and send us your review!</strong></h2>","productionOffice":"UK","trailText":"<strong>Adya@Youngbookreporters: </strong>‘a simple story made into such a touching and sad book’","headline":"Room on the Roof by Ruskin Bond - review","byline":"Adya@Youngbookreporters"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/mar/21/room-on-the-roof-ruskin-bond-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/2016/mar/21/room-on-the-roof-ruskin-bond-review","sectionName":"Children's books","elements":[{"id":"d98d062df1028815327860380319b0d7ff03eb6f","relation":"body","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/d98d062df1028815327860380319b0d7ff03eb6f/0_0_229_350/229.jpg","typeData":{"role":"thumbnail","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/d98d062df1028815327860380319b0d7ff03eb6f","altText":"The Room on the Roof","source":"PR","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"d98d062df1028815327860380319b0d7ff03eb6f","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/d98d062df1028815327860380319b0d7ff03eb6f/0_0_229_350/229.jpg","width":"229","height":"350"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/d98d062df1028815327860380319b0d7ff03eb6f/0_0_229_350/master/229.jpg","typeData":{"role":"thumbnail","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/d98d062df1028815327860380319b0d7ff03eb6f","altText":"The Room on the Roof","source":"PR","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"d98d062df1028815327860380319b0d7ff03eb6f","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/d98d062df1028815327860380319b0d7ff03eb6f/0_0_229_350/master/229.jpg","width":"229","height":"350","isMaster":"true"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"}]}],"tags":[{"id":"childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webTitle":"Children's books","type":"blog","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Children and teenagers","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/childrens-books-8-12-years","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Children's books: 8-12 years","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books-8-12-years","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/childrens-books-8-12-years","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","sectionId":"culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/adventure","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Adventure (children and teens)","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/adventure","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/adventure","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/friendship","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Friendship (children and teens)","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/friendship","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/friendship","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/childrens-user-reviews","webTitle":"Children's user reviews","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/childrens-user-reviews","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/childrens-user-reviews","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-03-21T10:57:38Z","webTitle":"Through my Window: the classic multicultural children's book – in pictures","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","type":"gallery","rights":{"syndicatable":"false"},"id":"childrens-books-site/gallery/2016/mar/21/through-my-window-multicultural-picture-book-tony-bradman-eileen-browne","fields":{"byline":"Tony Bradman and Eileen Browne","headline":"Through my Window: the classic multicultural children's book – in pictures","trailText":"Tony Bradman and Eileen Browne tell us the story behind their classic picture book published 30 years ago, featuring the first interracial family where the story wasn’t about race or culture in the UK and the US – as well as one of the earliest stay at home dads!<br>","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"007787bcce924feb99043478a4e0ee0273044d12\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/007787bcce924feb99043478a4e0ee0273044d12/0_0_2560_3225/794.jpg\" alt=\"Through my window\" width=\"794\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Tony Bradman: I met a woman called Janetta Otter-Barry in 1985 - she was the editor for Methuen Children’s Books. I’d done a few books for her, and then she asked if I could re-write a story that Eileen Browne had come up with about a little girl looking out of a (hospital) window. I thought a picture that Eileen had done was lovely, and it struck a chord with me - and I soon came up the idea of a little girl waiting for her dad to come home from work. That book became <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/367864/\">Through My Window</a>.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"17d0e141365eeec0b362c46bb7a9a750fa525ad4\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/17d0e141365eeec0b362c46bb7a9a750fa525ad4/0_0_2560_2938/871.jpg\" alt=\"Hospital\" width=\"871\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Tony Bradman:<em> </em>Eileen was keen for the star of the book, a little girl called Jo, to be mixed race. We also decided early on that the family should be urban and that mum would go to work. <br> <br>Eileen Browne: I’m white and all of my black friends at that time came from mixed-race families. Neither Tony or I realised that this would be the first picture book featuring an interracial family, where the story wasn’t about race or culture, in both the UK and the USA.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"b0850467e3f460a709488ef73ffe9bc53e1b6669\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/b0850467e3f460a709488ef73ffe9bc53e1b6669/0_0_1936_2592/747.jpg\" alt=\"Thumbnails\" width=\"747\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Eileen: Here’s a bit of background in how <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/367864/\">Through My Window</a> was made into a book. <br><br>Once the text is finalised, I break it into 12 double-page spreads and do quick “thumbnail” sketches of first ideas. Next, I make a tiny “dummy” book with pencil roughs and text on 32 pages, stapled together. The book is edited/re-drawn several times and the dummy books then get bigger!</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"ad471b449a50169d99d763b28f167cc8846ef4dd\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/ad471b449a50169d99d763b28f167cc8846ef4dd/0_0_2560_2524/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Dad at home\" width=\"1000\" height=\"986\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Tony: Eileen had suggested that Jo’s father should be the one who stays at home and looks after her when she doesn’t feel well and has a day off school.My children were young at the time, and I really believed dads should be equal partners in every aspect of family life. The mixed-race angle was unusual in picture books at the time, and I think stay-at-home dads were too!</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"0c186d894b0ee7ff916e755e4eb892ded191ed38\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/0c186d894b0ee7ff916e755e4eb892ded191ed38/0_0_572_640/447.jpg\" alt=\"Jo sketch\" width=\"447\" height=\"500\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Eileen: The black and white sketch I made for this picture also has little drawings of Jo’s face. I usually draw faces over and over again, to try and get the “right” expression!</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne sketch</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"22b26d3ee7bde99f05e2b5b4427685512f7b688b\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/22b26d3ee7bde99f05e2b5b4427685512f7b688b/0_0_2560_2606/982.jpg\" alt=\"Through my window 5\" width=\"982\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Tony: I love the way Eileen brings the urban setting to glorious life. It seemed to me at the time that most children’s picture books were set in a mythical idyllic or fantasy countryside which was nothing like the experience of most contemporary children. I grew up in a flat in south London and spent a lot of time looking out of the window waiting for my mum to come home from work. Eileen manages to make the street seem familiar, and also something rather wonderful too, despite the grime! <br><br></span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"de6b9a2539537d542b2154fdf262c0fb63e84cd3\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/de6b9a2539537d542b2154fdf262c0fb63e84cd3/39_207_2448_1470/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Street sketch\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Eileen: The street scenes (see my sketch on the right) were based on the view from my North London window. I was home-tutoring the boy in the striped jacket: a friend used to carry her toddler on the back of her bike: there <em>was</em> a cat asleep on a motor-bike! But the man pushing a baby in a pram was invented: it was a rare sight in the 1980s.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"3a90ae39e0bd041ca711a36246e09ddaa5e5e523\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/3a90ae39e0bd041ca711a36246e09ddaa5e5e523/0_0_2560_2369/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Picture 6\" width=\"1000\" height=\"925\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Tony: Of course the most obvious thing about <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/367864/\">Through My Window</a> is the fact that it’s very mutli-cultural, But we decided early on not to make any big, overt statement about how were should all get along - we just showed people doing exactly that! This is probably one of the quietest scenes in the book, but I love it - three people having tea together, one of them wistfully looking out of the window. What more needs to be said about how we’re all different but all the same?</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"3580b1c7125c10681ffc07ae6b3a6e4b4093cda6\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/3580b1c7125c10681ffc07ae6b3a6e4b4093cda6/0_0_640_478/640.jpg\" alt=\"Eileen Browne sketch on tracing paper\" width=\"640\" height=\"478\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Eileen: I love seeing Asian women wearing traditional clothes in London - but in cold weather, Mrs Ali would have worn a coat too. Dad’s slipper has a hole in the toe - as did that of my partner! In those days my sketches were often done on tracing paper and traced off through carbon paper onto watercolour board. (I now have the luxury of a light box!) The pen line was added after the water-colours.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"aff6f6c51a71dc5d525567993f38f66c67840a43\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/aff6f6c51a71dc5d525567993f38f66c67840a43/0_0_2560_1612/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Flats\" width=\"1000\" height=\"630\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Tony: I love the way Eileen has given the dog and cat so much character - Patch’s doggy excitement, the cat’s irritation. Kids love this when I read the story in schools. I also love the background, the block of flats with its balconies and all the people looking out. It’s just like the block up the road from where I grew up in Penge - and also like many of the flats where the kids whose schools I visit live with their families.<br><br>Eileen: My friends lived in a flat like these. There was no garden, so they let their baby crawl along the balcony - and get spectacularly filthy!</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"9a31a7053bfb1349d406b5d7013ae95b9aa17914\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/9a31a7053bfb1349d406b5d7013ae95b9aa17914/103_0_2457_2549/964.jpg\" alt=\"Through my window\" width=\"964\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Eileen: The swan with plastic flowers on the window-sill was based on a real ornament I had. It was a present from a boy after he went blind during the time I was teaching him. The man with a wooden leg pushing an old pram used to collect bric-a-brac from the streets. My friend and I learned to drive in the green VW Beetle (I’m in the back!). We bought it for £50 and sold it for the same amount after we’d passed our driving tests.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"85d8e00b2515421f78541e363d8b4e9b05d1e5ed\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/85d8e00b2515421f78541e363d8b4e9b05d1e5ed/0_0_2560_2017/1000.jpg\" alt=\"On the safa\" width=\"1000\" height=\"788\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Eileen: This is my favourite picture of the family. Mum’s home from work and has kicked off her shoes. Dad’s as keen as Jo to see what her surprise present can be. I relished the opportunity to put a typical (1980s) image on the box, of a white boy dressed in the doctor’s outfit, to contrast with the black girl actually wearing it on the following page.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"14fee9e9627157a069665d35cca0bf6588d93fc2\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/14fee9e9627157a069665d35cca0bf6588d93fc2/0_0_2560_2404/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Jo as Doctor\" width=\"1000\" height=\"939\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Tony: We decided that we would give the ending of the story a touch of aspiration. We could have ended the story with Jo in a nurse’s outfit. Now of course, being a nurse like her mum would be fine - nurses are great people who work hard to help others. But we wanted Jo to go even further - which is why we gave her a doctor’s outfit instead!</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"255bc762881f07918980fab461505518d6336616\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/255bc762881f07918980fab461505518d6336616/0_0_1890_2448/772.jpg\" alt=\"Through My window cover\" width=\"772\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">This was the original cover of Through My Window by Tony Bradman and Eileen Browne, published in 1986.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Eileen Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"4bd90c83dfa1d9dda4f73aad1b0a0bf5f63a869e\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/4bd90c83dfa1d9dda4f73aad1b0a0bf5f63a869e/0_0_2527_3189/792.jpg\" alt=\"Through my window\" width=\"792\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The 30th anniversary edition of <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/367864/\">Through My Window</a> is available from the Guardian bookshop.</span> </figcaption> </figure>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4h736","wordcount":"0","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/007787bcce924feb99043478a4e0ee0273044d12/0_924_2560_1536/140.jpg","stan