Books. I’d done a few books for her, and then she asked if I could re-write a story that Eileen Browne had come up with about a little girl looking out of a (hospital) window. I thought a picture that Eileen had done was lovely, and it struck a chord with me - and I soon came up the idea of a little girl waiting for her dad to come home from work. That book became <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/367864/\">Through My Window</a>.","source":"Eileen Browne","credit":"Illustration: Eileen Browne","mediaId":"007787bcce924feb99043478a4e0ee0273044d12","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Illustration","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/007787bcce924feb99043478a4e0ee0273044d12/0_0_2560_3225/397.jpg","width":"397","height":"500"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"}]},{"id":"17d0e141365eeec0b362c46bb7a9a750fa525ad4","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/17d0e141365eeec0b362c46bb7a9a750fa525ad4/0_0_2560_2938/2560.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/17d0e141365eeec0b362c46bb7a9a750fa525ad4","altText":"Hospital","caption":"Tony Bradman:<em> </em>Eileen was keen for the star of the book, a little girl called Jo, to be mixed race. We also decided early on that the family should be urban and that mum would go to work. <br> <br>Eileen Browne: I’m white and all of my black friends at that time came from mixed-race families. Neither Tony or I realised that this would be the first picture book featuring an interracial family, where the story wasn’t about race or culture, in both the UK and the USA.","source":"Eileen Browne","credit":"Illustration: Eileen Browne","mediaId":"17d0e141365eeec0b362c46bb7a9a750fa525ad4","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Illustration","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/17d0e141365eeec0b362c46bb7a9a750fa525ad4/0_0_2560_2938/2560.jpg","width":"2560","height":"2938"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/17