iew/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"id":"childrens-books-site/2016/mar/21/one-of-us-jeannie-waudby-review","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"type":"article","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webTitle":"One of Us by Jeannie Waudby - review","webPublicationDate":"2016-03-21T09:00:04Z","fields":{"wordcount":"428","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4h6n8","standfirst":"<p>‘Jeannie Waudby’s debut novel is exciting and impossible to put down’</p>","body":"<p>One of Us is a remarkable tale which reminds us that there is a difference between what is right and what is easy, as well as the fact that the people who we believe to be our mortal enemies aren’t so very different from us after all. At a time when the world is filled with huge divides between sexes, races, religions and more, this book couldn’t be more fitting. </p> <p>The heroine, K, begins by hating a group named ‘The Brotherhood’ because it’s what she’s been taught to do but when she’s sent on an undercover mission by Oskar, she realises that the people who she believed to be inhumane monsters are actually human beings, just like her. </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"276741ace630655cb6a818a18c58ae8c6f6cdbe2\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/276741ace630655cb6a818a18c58ae8c6f6cdbe2/0_0_310_475/310.jpg\" alt=\"One of Us\" width=\"310\" height=\"475\" class=\"gu-image\" /> </figure>  <p>The world that K lives in is very similar to our own, with two warring ‘tribes’ called ‘The Brotherhood’ and ‘The Citizens’ attempting to co-exist following a twelve­ year ­long battle known as ‘the Strife’ and each believes that they’re better than the other and that their ideologies are right. However, the majority of ‘Citizens’ and ‘Hoods’ don’t take things to the extreme of bombing a tube station. And that’s where the story begins. Twelve years prior to the start of the story, there was a similar bombing at ‘Central Station’ that was blamed on a pair of suicide bombers from the Brotherhood. Twelve years later, following another bombing which people fear will make the Strife begin again, K pretends to be the bomber’s daughter, Verity Nekton, in order to gain access to the Brotherhood and all it’s secrets. <br /> <br />However, whilst K initially embarks on her mission determined to discover a sleeper cell of potential bombers, she discovers a history which stretches way back to before she was born and she begins to question what is good and bad and whether the people that she believes she’s working for are actually on the ‘good’ side after all. <br /> <br />Overall, One of Us is a compelling story about how terrorism ravages our society as well as how in a world which seems to be hard and lacking compassion, human love can triumph even in the most impossible of circumstances. Jeannie Waudby’s debut novel is exciting and impossible to put down, with action and even a little romance present on each page and I can honestly say that I’d thoroughly recommend it.</p> <p><strong>• Buy this book at the <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/one-of-us.html\">Guardian Bookshop</a></strong></p> <h2><strong>Want to tell the world about a book you’ve read? <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">Join the site</a> and send us your review!</strong></h2>","productionOffice":"UK","trailText":"<strong>Tasha:</strong> ‘Jeannie Waudby’s debut novel is exciting and impossible to put down’ ","headline":"One of Us by Jeannie Waudby - review","byline":"Tasha"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/mar/21/one-of-us-jeannie-waudby-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/2016/mar/21/one-of-us-jeannie-waudby-review","sectionName":"Children's books","elements":[{"id":"276741ace630655cb6a818a18c58ae8c6f6cdbe2","relation":"body","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/2767