"Soul","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/music/soul","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/music/soul","sectionName":"Music","references":[]},{"id":"tone/reviews","webTitle":"Reviews","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/reviews","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/reviews","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"profile/juderogers","webTitle":"Jude Rogers","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Jude Rogers writes for publications including the Observer, Guardian, New Statesman, Marie Claire and Q. She also appears on TV and radio and is a Journalism BA lecturer at London Metropolitan University</p>","bylineImageUrl":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/1/4/1357311858105/JudeRogersprofilepicJan2012.jpg","firstName":"jude","lastName":"rogers","r2ContributorId":"23517","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/juderogers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/juderogers","references":[]},{"id":"publication/theobserver","sectionId":"theobserver","webTitle":"The Observer","type":"publication","description":"From the Observer, the Sunday newspaper and sister publication of the Guardian.","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/all","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/publication/theobserver","sectionName":"From the Observer","references":[]},{"id":"theobserver/new-review","sectionId":"culture","webTitle":"The New Review","type":"newspaper-book","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/new-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theobserver/new-review","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"theobserver/new-review/books","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Books","type":"newspaper-book-section","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/new-review/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theobserver/new-review/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-03-21T07:00:02Z","webTitle":"Games reviews roundup: Tom Clancy’s The Division; Pokkén Tournament; Samurai Warriors 4: Empires","sectionId":"technology","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"technology/2016/mar/21/tom-clancy-division-pokken-tournament-samurai-warriors-empires-games-reviews","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Matt Kamen","headline":"Games reviews roundup: Tom Clancy’s The Division; Pokkén Tournament; Samurai Warriors 4: Empires","trailText":"Battle commences in a terrorised New York, the Pokémon arena and feudal Japan","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p></p> <h2><a href=\"http://tomclancy-thedivision.ubi.com/game/en-gb/home/\" title=\"\"><strong>Tom Clancy’s The Division</strong></a></h2> <p>(PS4, Xbox One, PC, Ubisoft, cert 18, out now)</p> <p>★★★★</p> <p>You can hardly fault <em>The Division</em> for ambition – Ubisoft’s open-world shooter/RPG hybrid takes place in an accurately mapped and meticulously detailed recreation of New York in the wake of a bio-terror attack. Despite the urban turmoil facing the player as a member of the titular organisation charged with restoring order, it’s hard not to be impressed by the sheer scale.</p> <p>Thankfully, it’s more than just an impressive facade. Although the similarities to the likes of <em>Destiny</em> or <em>Borderlands</em> are undeniable, <em>The Division</em> improves on both in key areas. Weapon choice matters, each gun feeling notably different to wield, while character build – such as combat preference, choice of support skills, and gear load-outs – has a notable impact on both solo play and effectiveness in a team.</p> <p>However, while story missions have varied objectives, actual gameplay often boils down to diving for cover and shooting enough enemies to progress. For all its charms elsewhere, familiarity is <em>The Division</em>’s worst enemy.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"e98b42cd44b4ef8974e9a386abe3e2778c505791\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/e98b42cd44b4ef8974e9a386abe3e2778c505791/115_0_1085_651/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Pokkén Tournament.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Pokémon meets Tekken in Pokkén Tournament.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <h2><a href=\"http://www.pokkentournament.com/en-gb/\" title=\"\"><strong>Pokkén Tournament</strong></a></h2> <p>(Wii U, Nintendo, cert: 7, out now)</p> <p>★★★★</p> <p>A <em>Tekken</em> spinoff featuring Pokémon characters may seem a strange prospect, but in fact <em>Pokkén Tournament </em>fulfils a promise the original Game Boy entries made 20 years ago – actual, real-time Pokémon battles. Surprisingly, <em>Pokkén</em> is also a more than competent fighting game. There’s a depth to battle mechanics belied by the colourful spectacle of seeing Pikachu and pals unleashed, and while it won’t dethrone more hardcore titles, it is solid enough to stand alongside them.</p> <p>However, <em>Pokkén</em> does play quite differently to its peers. Each round shifts between “field phase”, where players test limits with ranged attacks, searching for openings, and “duel phase”, where the up-close <em>Tekken</em> influence becomes clear. Special moves are perhaps too simple to use, but here it’s timing rather than complex combos that matter. Most importantly, it’s well balanced. Like the RPGs, each Pokémon has strengths and weaknesses that canny players will be able to leverage to victory. A curiosity to be sure, but a fantastic one.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"1ecbffa63a3ec363359388e3eb31af7cd40d8f4a\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/1ecbffa63a3ec363359388e3eb31af7cd40d8f4a/59_0_1799_1080/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Samurai Warriors 4: Empires.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Battle commences in feudal Japan in Samurai Warriors 4: Empires.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <h2><a href=\"http://www.samuraiwarriors4.eu/empires/\" title=\"\"><strong>Samurai Warriors 4: Empires</strong></a></h2> <p>(PS4, PS3, Koei Tecmo, cert: 12, out now)</p> <p>★★★</p> <p>The sheer volume of <em>Warriors</em> games often reduces the franchise to an indistinct blur of swordplay and fallen foes. The <em>Samurai Warriors</em> sub-series is, arguably, guiltiest of all, each offering only minor variations on gameplay while retreading key battles in Japan’s feudal history.</p> <p>Thankfully, <em>Empires</em> makes waging the likes of the Battle of Sekigahara – again – a more enticing prospect, blending familiar hack-and-slash with a hefty dose of actual strategy and resource management. As one of several daimyo, players tackle rival clans seeking either national dominion or more personal objectives, while engaging in politics between conflicts. Building a castle and taking counsel from advisers has a direct impact on military strength, while relationships between your lieutenants can affect resource production and, in turn, a burgeoning empire.</p> <p>With new features such as political marriages, series devotees will find plenty of nuanced details to warrant returning, while newcomers and sceptics may be surprised by the balance of tactical depth and cathartic – if repetitive – action.</p>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4hjqp","wordcount":"541","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/508e7fdbf4521b44b4f20d1b28be2c5a7f542680/0_110_1390_834/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-04-11T07:00:00Z","standfirst":"New York is convincingly terrorised in a biological attack, Pokémon meets Tekken in the arena, and it’s not all swords and samurais in feudal Japan"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/mar/21/tom-clancy-division-pokken-tournament-samurai-warriors-empires-games-reviews","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/technology/2016/mar/21/tom-clancy-division-po