 Unknown British photographer, photogenic drawing\" width=\"1000\" height=\"852\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Fern Leaves, c1850<br></strong><strong>Unknown British photographer, p</strong><strong>hotogenic drawing</strong><br><br>Author Eugenia Parry wrote of Wagstaff: ‘He changed the game. That was the talk. But in the early 1970s there was no game. Sam gave photography collection a decisive direction … He was photography’s main disciple. How he achieved this distinction was his secret’</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: J Paul Getty Trust</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"f1459c98246e5a2ef576573c7abbfda7cbcede05\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/f1459c98246e5a2ef576573c7abbfda7cbcede05/0_27_3448_4448/775.jpg\" alt=\"Lupus Vulgaris, 1900. Oscar G Mason (US, 1830–1921), from Photographic Atlas of the Diseases of the Skin (1900), by Dr George Henry Fox, hand-coloured halftone\" width=\"775\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Lupus Vulgaris, 1900<br></strong><strong>F</strong><strong>rom Photographic Atlas of the Diseases of the Skin (1900), by Dr George Henry Fox. </strong><strong>Oscar G Mason (US, 1830–1921),</strong><strong> hand-coloured halftone</strong><br><br>Getty Museum curator Weston Naef said: ‘We will be for ever grateful to Sam Wagstaff for opening our eyes to the beauty in types of photographs that were once classed by experts as irrelevant to the history of art, and for his ability to recognise the subtle beauties of photographs that were not created as works of art’</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Oscar G Mason/J Paul Getty Trust</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"57a465e9703d14ccfc7b6cd08531d3932b537dcc\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/57a465e9703d14ccfc7b6cd08531d3932b537dcc/0_5_2493_2951/845.jpg\" alt=\"Portrait of a black man wearing a bow tie (Gentleman Caller), c1856. Unknown photographer, US, daguerreotype\" width=\"845\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Portrait of a black man wearing a bow tie (Gentleman Caller), c1856<br></strong><strong>Unknown photographer, US, daguerreotype <br></strong><br>Wagstaff’s collection spans early experiments in the mid-19th century like this one, right up to photos from the 1970s.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: J Paul Getty Museum</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"a11ff709d16266d709275ce33f860cc8ff5cf5e9\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/a11ff709d16266d709275ce33f860cc8ff5cf5e9/0_14_2130_3146/677.jpg\" alt=\"Standing Girl with Violin, 1896–98. Gertrude Käsebier (US, 1852–1934), platinum print\" width=\"677\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Standing Girl with Violin, 1896–98<br></strong><strong>Gertrude Käsebier (US, 1852–1934), p</strong><strong>latinum print</strong><br><br>After amassing his thousands of photos, Wagstaff sold the collection to the Getty in 1984, and began instead championing American works of silver decorative art</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Gertrude Käsebier/J Paul Getty Trust</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"199529cc8a43d00053a535368c2afebab63de94b\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/199529cc8a43d00053a535368c2afebab63de94b/0_0_3348_1502/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Lilacs, c1898. Auguste Lumière (French, 1862–1954), Louis Lumière (1862–1948), All-Chroma stereoscopic autochrome\" width=\"1000\" height=\"449\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Lilacs, c1898<br></strong><strong>Auguste Lumière (French, 1862–1954), Louis Lumière (1862–1948), All-Chroma stereoscopic autochrome<br></strong><br>Wagstaff became friends with some of New York’s most iconoclastic artists, like proto-punk musician Patti Smith, who said of him: ‘We liked each other immediately. He had such a great sense of humour and had such a nonpretentious and nonsanctimonious spiritual air.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Auguste Lumière/J Paul Getty Museum</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"a9cef455b43e92275a3bd2c36302852619d2b0e5\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/a9cef455b43e92275a3bd2c36302852619d2b0e5/0_0_4756_4730/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Winchester Cathedral, the Nave, West, c1883, Frederick H Evans (British, 1853–1943), lantern slide\" width=\"1000\" height=\"995\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Winchester Cathedral, the Nave, West, c1883<br></strong><strong>Frederick H Evans (British, 1853–1943), </strong><strong>lantern slide</strong><br><br>Closeted in the 1950s, Wagstaff embraced the debauched lifestyle of gay New York with his lover Mapplethorpe. Christie’s director Philippe Garner says in a documentary about Wagstaff: ‘My guess is that Robert gave Sam the courage to explore areas of his personality, to savour a darker kind of lifestyle than he would have done on his own. He unlocked a dark genie within him’</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Frederick H Evans/J Paul Getty Trust</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"1fa86d35f17f3a6c16db8242b7d09ea3f4417f5c\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/1fa86d35f17f3a6c16db8242b7d09ea3f4417f5c/1_7_1996_1636/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Butterflies 1935; Man Ray (US, 1890-1976), Carbro print\" width=\"1000\" height=\"820\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Butterflies 1935<br></strong><strong>Man Ray (US, 1890-1976), C</strong><strong>arbro print</strong><br><br>Mapplethorpe himself said of their relationship: ‘I was a real hippie. Sam was a real hippie, too. Financially, he certainly helped me. He was very generous. We never actually lived together. I had a loft on Bond Street which he bought for me. He had a loft on Bond Street too. We were lovers as well … It lasted a couple of years. Then we became best friends. I even introduced him to James Nelson, who became his boyfriend after me’</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: J Paul Getty Museum</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"1b7796227014c6d9f09d6e91460f25a086be5cec\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/1b7796227014c6d9f09d6e91460f25a086be5cec/0_0_1965_3145/625.jpg\" alt=\"Case of John Frederick U.S.N. with Compensatory Apparatus by ED Hudson, MD, c1864. Attributed to William H Bell (US, 1830–1910), No 3, albumen silver\" width=\"625\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Case of John Frederick USN with Compensatory Apparatus by ED Hudson, MD, c1864<br></strong><strong>Attributed to William H Bell (US, 1830–1910), No 3, a</strong><strong>lbumen silver</strong><br><br>The couple’s sexual relationship evolved into a lasting friendship, until Wagstaff’s Aids-related death from pneumonia in 1987. He left Mapplethorpe his estate in his will, which was contested in legal proceedings started – and later dropped – by Wagstaff’s sister</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: William H Bell/J Paul Getty Museum</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"35322b648507e6af5e87446eb7a111f0f8f80576\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/35322b648507e6af5e87446eb7a111f0f8f80576/0_0_2883_3631/794.jpg\" alt=\"Portrait of a Seated Girl, c1850. Unknown US daguerreotypist\" width=\"794\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Portrait of a Seated Girl, c1850<br></strong><strong>Unknown US daguerreotypist</strong><br><br>When Patti Smith visited Sam Wagstaff in his final days, he told her: ‘I have only loved three things in my life. Robert, my mother, and art’</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: J Paul Getty Trust</span> </figcaption> </figure>","productionOffice":"UK","trailText":"Samuel J Wagstaff Jr – a New York aristocrat, curator and Robert Mapplethorpe’s lover – collected over 26,000 photographs in his lifetime, of everything from grisly medical images to eerie portraits","headline":"Pieces of a man: the passions of photo collector Samuel J Wagstaff – in pictures"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2016/mar/21/pieces-of-a-man-the-passions-of-photo-collector-samuel-j-wagstaff-in-pictures","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/artanddesign/gallery/2016/mar/21/pieces-of-a-man-the-passions-of-photo-collector-samuel-j-wagstaff-in-pictures","sectionName":"Art and design","elements":[{"id":"6e7f699d28dad8f15446a6978f187fe888b03b5f","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/6e7f699d28dad8f15446a6978f187fe888b03b5f/0_0_2516_3128/2516.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/6e7f699d28dad8f15446a6978f187fe888b03b5f","suppliersReference":"Dinornis Elephantopus","altText":"Dinornis Elephantopus, 1854–1858. Roger Fenton (English, 1819–69), salted paper print","caption":"<strong>Dinornis Elephantopus, 1854–1858<br></strong><strong>Roger Fenton (English, 1819–69), s</strong><strong>alted paper print<br><br></strong>In 1973, Samuel Wagstaff began collecting photographs, determined for them to be accepted as a valid art form. Over the next decade he amassed more than 26,000 images. Roger Fenton photographed the extinct moa’s reconstructed skeleton at the British Museum<br><br><br>• The exhibition <a href=\"http://www.getty.edu/visit/cal/events/ev_431.html\">The Thrill of the Chase: The Wagst